</user_query>"}]},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This happens when all your reminders’ times are in the past or **exactly at or before the current system time** at the moment of scheduling, or being re-scheduled when the app resumes. 
When you launch your app, if you reschedule old reminders (with time already passed), AlarmManager will trigger them immediately, firing all notifications at once.

---

## Why is this happening?

- **AlarmManager.setExactAndAllowWhileIdle** (or any scheduling API) will immediately fire alarms if the scheduled time (`reminder.dateTime`) is less than or equal to now when (re)scheduling.
- Your code might "resend" these on app open if you call scheduling logic for all reminders, no matter if they're in the past or future.

---

## How to fix it:

### 1. **Schedule only future reminders**
Update your scheduling logic to check if the reminder's scheduled time is in the future:

```kotlin
if (reminder.dateTime > System.currentTimeMillis()) {
 scheduleReminderUseCase.invoke(reminder, context)
 appPreferences.addScheduledReminderId(reminder.id)
}
```
Do the same for update.

### 2. **Optionally, remove old reminders from prefs/cancel schedule**
When loading reminders or on app start, remove expired reminders from DataStore to keep it in sync.

---

## Example fix for your ViewModel:

**In addReminder and updateReminder:**

```kotlin
fun addReminder(reminder: Reminder) {
 viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) {
 val userReminder = reminder.copy(userId = userId)
 repository.addReminder(userReminder)
 if (userReminder.dateTime > System.currentTimeMillis()) {
 scheduleReminderUseCase.invoke(userReminder, context)
 appPreferences.addScheduledReminderId(userReminder.id)
 } else {
 scheduleReminderUseCase.scheduler.cancel(userReminder, context)
 appPreferences.removeScheduledReminderId(userReminder.id)
 }
 loadReminders()
 }
}
```

**The same check goes in updateReminder.**

---

**Summary:**
- Only schedule notifications for future reminders.
- Remove (cancel) any "old" scheduled reminders immediately, or just do nothing if they’re expired.

